<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-083-390 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 100 951  OV: 11 100 935.andM; </DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  August 12 1991 v8 n32 p77(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Central Point Software Inc.: PC Tools 7.0. (Software Review) (oneof four evaluations of file-recovery programs in '4 utilitiesrecover damaged dBASE files.') (evaluation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Chernicoff, David P.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>The Filefix utility in Central Point Software's popular PC Tools7.0 general-purpose utility package can diagnose and repairdamaged dBASE, Lotus 1-2-3 and Symphony files.andP;  It is similar toits counterpart in the competing Norton Utilities package butslightly slower; the interface is cleaner, and users can view therepaired file from within the repair program.andP;  Filefix isextremely tolerant of file-header damage, automatically recoveringall lost data but introducing errors into the first 10 records ofa 10,000-record file.andP;  There is no support for editing files inhexadecimal form, and documentation is weak when it comes torepairing dBASE files.andP;  The PC Tools 7.0 package sells for $179.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Central Point Software Inc. (Products).andO;Product:   dBASE (Data base management system) (evaluation)PC Tools 7.0 (File management software) (evaluation).andO;Topic:     Utility programsEvaluationSoftware PackagesFile Management.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Vital signs. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Central Point Software Inc.andM;PC TOOLS 7.0andM;Filefix is just a small tool in PC Tools' Data Recovery and SystemsUtilities, which themselves are a subset of what Central Point Softwarerefers to as &quot;Essential Utilities for the PC Professional.&quot;andM;PC Tools' Filefix damaged-file-recovery utility diagnoses and repairs damageddBASE, Lotus 1-2-3 and Symphony files.andM;Similar to Norton Utilities' Filefix, PC Tools' Filefix performed onlyslightly more slowly in PC Week Labs' tests, and it provides a somewhatcleaner interface and the ability to view the repaired file from within therepair program.andM;Extremely tolerant of the file-header damage introduced in PC Week Labs' Test2 (bad header information and an invalid field name), PC Tools' Filefix wasthe only program of those reviewed that automatically recovered the data.andO;Filefix introduced errors into the first 10 records of a 10,000-record file,however, and although the errors were easily repaired in dBASE, it's aconsideration when judging Filefix's automated-repair capability.andM;When PC Week Labs ran the same test with a manual assist to the recovery, thefirst 10 records were still damaged.andM;As in Norton Utilities, the ability to edit the file in hex is not supportedin Filefix.andP;  That capability is supported by the hex editor in PC Tools' PCShell utility.andM;Central Point Software's skimpy 10 pages of information on repairing dBASEfiles do not provide a very comprehensive explanation of the process.andM;------------------&quot;VITAL SIGNS&quot; DATAandM;Central Point Software Inc.andM;Beaverton, Ore.andM;(800) 445-2110 or (503) 690-8090andM;Privately heldandM;Year established: 1981andM;Number of employees: 300andplus;andM;Gross annual revenueandM;(fiscal 1991): $53.8 millionandM;Gross annual earnings:andM;not disclosedandM;Source.andP;  Information supplied by company.andM;</TEXT></DOC>